text:
Rada approves bill to prevent money laundering

01 Nov 2019, 15:05


The Verkhovna Rada adopted as a basis bill 2179 on the prevention and counteraction to the legalization (laundering) of proceeds of crime, terrorist financing and the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.

The live broadcast is by ZIK.
278 people's deputies voted for the corresponding decision.
As stated in the explanatory note, the draft law proposes to comprehensively improve national legislation on financial monitoring, in particular as regards:

introduction of common terminology in the field of prevention and counteraction to the legalization (laundering) of proceeds of crime, terrorist financing and financing of the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and its essence to international ones;
applying the risk-oriented approach of the primary financial monitoring entities (SPFMs) in conducting due diligence of their clients and accordingly moving to case reports on suspicious transactions (activities) of their clients;
raising the threshold and reducing the number of mandatory financial reporting features that PFMS (banks, insurers, credit unions, pawnshops, exchanges, payment institutions and other financial institutions) were obliged to report to SCFM, to report on financial transactions in the amount of more than UAH 400 thousand. (now UAH 150 thousand) and related to cash, money transfer abroad, politically significant persons and clients from countries that do not follow the recommendations of international, intergovernmental organizations active in the field of anti-legalization;
expansion of the SPFM range that will inform SCFM about suspicious financial transactions - by persons providing tax advisory services;
improving the procedure for disclosure by entities of their ultimate beneficial owners (controllers) and strengthening the requirements for identifying SPFMs of beneficial owners of their clients;
introduction of an international asset freeze tool and regulation of SPFM actions with assets related to terrorism and its financing;
improvement of legislative aspects that affect the quality of criminal investigations into the legalization (laundering) of proceeds from crime;
improvement of the provisions of the legislation, which ensure confidentiality of the fact of receipt and execution of SPFM requests, decisions and orders of SCFM, and, as a consequence, protection of the SPFM from threats, discriminatory actions and other negative consequences related to the implementation of measures of primary financial monitoring;
moving to money transfer tracking as a tool to prevent, detect and investigate cases of money laundering and terrorist financing, and to take restrictive measures.

The Bill introduces an obligation for payment systems:

to accompany money transfers with information about the payer and the payee;
ensure the availability and completeness of information about the payer and payee;
to establish preventive measures aimed at counteracting the manipulation of money obtained from crimes related to the legalization (laundering) of proceeds from crime, the financing of terrorism.

An online broadcast of the morning session of Parliament is available at the link.


